<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="191" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[111,648,1230,1700]" box="[113,213,1230,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[111,648,1230,1700]" lastBlockId="2.[674,1210,1230,1320]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
Relationships among the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cox &amp; Knight" authorityYear="1960" box="[400,530,1261,1288]" class="Gastropoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neritopsina" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="order">Neritopsina</taxonomicName>
are in the course of study. The slug genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Bergh, 1975" authorityName="Bergh" authorityYear="1975" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritopsidae" genus="Titiscania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cycloneritida" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[463,566,1294,1319]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Titiscania</emphasis>
Bergh, 1975
</taxonomicName>
which previously had an uncertain systematic position, has been included in this clade (
<bibRefCitation author="KANO Y. &amp; CHIBA S. &amp; KASE T." pageId="2" pageNumber="191" pagination="2457 - 2465" refId="ref4685" refString="KANO Y., CHIBA S. &amp; KASE T. 2002. - Major adaptive radiation in neritopsine gastropods estimated from 28 S rRNA sequences and fossil records. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, B 269: 2457 - 2465." type="journal article" year="2002">
Kano 
<emphasis box="[599,640,1356,1382]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
). The ecological radiation of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cox &amp; Knight" authorityYear="1960" box="[520,647,1388,1415]" class="Gastropoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neritopsina" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="order">Neritopsina</taxonomicName>
is remarkable. Originating from shallow water, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cox &amp; Knight" authorityYear="1960" box="[115,240,1451,1478]" class="Gastropoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neritopsina" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="order">Neritopsina</taxonomicName>
have invaded fresh water and terrestrial environments, and live also in brackish waters and in anchialine waters (defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="KANO Y. &amp; KASE T." box="[426,647,1515,1542]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" pagination="423 - 437" refId="ref4645" refString="KANO Y. &amp; KASE T. 2004. - Genetic exchange between anchialine cave populations by means of larval dispersal: the case of a new gastropod species Neritilia cavernicola. Zoologica Scripta 33: 423 - 437." type="journal article" year="2004">Kano &amp; Kase [2004]</bibRefCitation>
as “bodies of haline water with more or less extensive subterranean connections to the sea, and showing noticeable marine as well as terrestrial influences”). They have colonised deep-sea hydrothermal vents and seeps, and the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[256,389,1673,1700]" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cycloneritida" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Neritopsidae</taxonomicName>
take refuge in submarine caves.Preliminary results based on partial 28S rRNA sequence (
<bibRefCitation author="KANO Y. &amp; CHIBA S. &amp; KASE T." box="[785,970,1261,1288]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" pagination="2457 - 2465" refId="ref4685" refString="KANO Y., CHIBA S. &amp; KASE T. 2002. - Major adaptive radiation in neritopsine gastropods estimated from 28 S rRNA sequences and fossil records. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, B 269: 2457 - 2465." type="journal article" year="2002">
Kano 
<emphasis box="[855,906,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">et al.</emphasis>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
) demonstrate that the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[677,814,1293,1320]" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cycloneritida" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Neritopsidae</taxonomicName>
is a very distinct, archaic clade.
</paragraph>
